{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"title":"Pappadums","content":["Place a jug onto mixing bowl lid and weigh water into it. Set jug aside.","Place urad dal into mixing bowl and mill <b>2 min\/speed 10<b>.","Add salt and chilli and knead <b>2 min\/<b>, slowly pouring water onto mixing bowl lid and letting it trickle into mixing bowl.","Add 1 tablespoon of the oil and knead <b>1 min\/<b>, until a hard, crumbly dough forms.","Transfer onto a silicone bread mat or work surface and shape into a ball. Clean and dry mixing bowl.","Divide dough into 15 pieces and roll into balls. Press each ball into a small disc and brush each side with oil. Using a rolling pin, place 1 dough portion between 2 sheets of baking paper and roll out thinly. Turn baking paper and continue rolling to form a paper-thin circle (see Tips). Set aside (uncovered) while rolling remaining pappadums.","Place a medium saucepan over high heat and place oil (4 cm high) into it. Bring oil to 180°C (use a kitchen thermometer, or drop a small cube of bread into oil; it should turn golden brown in 15 seconds). Using tongs, place 1 pappadum into hot oil; it will puff up immediately. Carefully turn over using tongs and fry for 2-3 more seconds until golden, then use tongs to remove to paper towels to drain. Repeat with remaining pappadums. Serve immediately or transfer into a sealable container and store at room temperature."]},{"title":"Mint and coriander chutney","content":["Place all chutney ingredients into mixing bowl and mix <b>30 sec\/speed 8<b>.","Transfer into a sealable storage container and place into refrigerator until ready to serve with pappadums."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"Pappadums","content":["180 g water","400 g urad dal , whole or split, husks removed (see Tips)","1 tsp fine salt","1 tsp chilli powder","1 tbsp vegetable oil, plus 300-500 g extra for rolling and frying"]},{"title":"Mint and coriander chutney","content":["12 sprigs fresh mint, leaves only","10 sprigs fresh coriander, leaves only","1 long green chilli, cut into halves and deseeded","1 tsp salt flakes","1 lime, juice only (approx. 20 g)","150 g natural yoghurt"]}],"id":"r114662","imageLink":"https:\/\/4.bp.blogspot.com\/-TmfzdyMupkQ\/XZWZTek03UI\/AAAAAAAAeK0\/GlA5PaJZLrMTIAZ-ZfZxUL9qfhU7PeSbgCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_Z1jcX-G2Y0K994Rw.png","title":"Pappadums with mint and coriander chutney","publishedAt":"2017-01-22T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"7.2 g","fat":"2.2 g","uom":"per 1 portions","carbohydrates":"14.2 g","calories":"479 kJ \/ 114 kcal"},"usefulItems":"jug, silicone bread mat, pastry brush, baking paper, rolling pin, paper towel, saucepan, sealable container, stove top, refrigerator","hintsAndTricks":["Urad dal is available from Indian grocers. It is a black-skinned lentil, but the lentil itself is a creamy colour. Ask for dehusked urad dal.","Roll pappadums as thinly as you can, until you can see your fingers through the dough.","Pappadums can be cooked in a dry frying pan, but they won't puff up as much. Place a large, heavy-based frypan over medium-high heat and toast pappadums until they bubble (approx. 1 minute). Carefully turn using tongs and fry for another 1 minute, or until light golden brown and crisp."],"basicInfo":["easy","45m","50m","15 portions"]}